boxinformationtooltip.title: Fill Information
boxinformationtooltip.text:
Specification for title name:
  •     • Specify a name or keep suggested one.
  •     • 3 - 20 characters.
  •     • Must be unique - duplicate names are not allowed.

boxmethodonepointtooltip.title: One Point Method
text_list:
•     • Specify the position and orientation of the center of the box.
  •     • Specify the box dimensions relative to the center of the box in +-X, +-Y, +-Z directions.

To specify the center point:
  • Manually enter values for the position and orientation of the center point.
  • Alternatively, tap TCP pose to fill in the values for the current TCP position.
  • Specify the box dimensions in X-, Y-, Z- directions.

boxmethodonepointtcpposetooltip.title: TCP Pose
boxmethodonepointtcpposetooltip.text: By default the Pose is selected. Upon clicking the Capture TCP Pose, the values are displayed and subsequently marked as Done.

boxmethodthreepointtooltip.title: Three Point Method
text_list:
• Specify the selected points with coordinates (X, Y, Z) to create a bounding box.
  • Specify the Height (e.g. in mm). Additionally Height can be positive (upward) or negative (downward) depending on the desired direction.

• Pose 1: The first point sets the origin of the new bounding box.
  • By Default the Pose 1 selected: Move the robot to the desired origin and RECORD this position by clicking Capture TCP Pose.
  • IMPORTANT: All three poses(1,2,and 3) must be defined. Otherwise, the bounding box cannot be created correctly.

• Pose 2: Defines the direction and length of the base edge.
  • Define the Pose 2: Move the robot to a point desired direction of the box's length and RECORD this position. The vector Pose 1 and 2 sets the direction of the box's base.

• Pose 3: Define the width direction of the bounding box by forming a plane with Points 1 and 2.
  • Establish the Bounding Box's plane: Move the robot to a point that is not on the line between 1 and 2.
• Height: Specify the vertical extent of the bounding box. The box is extruded upward (Positive) or downward (Negative) depending on desired direction.

• By default, the First Pose is selected. Upon clicking the Capture TCP Pose, the values are displayed and subsequently marked as Done.
  • If values are added for all the poses(1,2, and 3), you can navigate between poses to modify the values and click Capture TCP Pose again.

boundingboxtypes.title: Bounding Box Types
boundingboxtypes.text:
Configure the box types:
  • NoGoArea: The robot is not allowed to enter inside the box.
  • Safe Zone: If the robot enters the safe zone box, one or several of the following are applied: Maximum TCP Speed, or Maximum Joint Speeds for all axes.

activateDeactivateBoxes.title: Activate/Deactivate Boxes
activateDeactivateBoxes.text:
You can enable bounding boxes created with the Wizard through the robot's settings:

NOTE!
  • You can have up to ten bounding boxes activated at the same time.
  • To activate a NoGoArea box, the robot must be positioned outside the box.

popup.revert_title: Revert Validation of Current Robot Configuration
popup.explanation_text: The robot's settings have changed, creating a new configuration checksum. This checksum is not validated, so the robot cannot be fully operated.
popup.validated_description: The current configuration checksum is validated. All features are available.
popup.not_validated_description: The current configuration is not validated. Normal users cannot operate the robot if the checksum of the current configuration is not validated.
popup.validation_confirmation: This will mark the checksum of the current robot configuration as validated. It allows all users to execute programs and use teach mode.
popup.revert_confirmation: The current configuration is marked as not validated. Normal users cannot operate the robot if the checksum of the current robot configuration is not validated.
popup.features_disabled: Features like jogging, ZeroG, and program execution are currently disabled.
popup.contact_admin: Please contact your superadmin to validate the configuration and restore full functionality.
popup.permission_notice: Only the Superadmin and other dedicated users can validate the checksum.
popup.note_content: These updates may affect robot behavior. Ensure all parameters are correct and intentional.
popup.no_action_required: No further action required unless additional changes are made.
popup.mismatch_note_content: This update includes changes to core configuration files that may impact robot behavior. Ensure all parameters have been verified.

safety_warning.title: Robot Configuration Change
safety_warning.message: Changing the {settingName} settings will invalidate the current configuration and a new checksum is created. Re-validation of the robot configuration is required afterwards.
safety_warning.restore_message: Restoring the {settingName} settings will invalidate the current configuration and a new checksum is created. Re-validation of the robot configuration is required afterwards.

program_blocking.title: Program Execution Blocked
program_blocking.message: Cannot play program due to unvalidated checksum. Only the Superadmin and other dedicated users can validate the checksum.
program_blocking.jogging_message: Cannot jog robot due to unvalidated checksum. Only the Superadmin and other dedicated users can validate the checksum.
program_blocking.robot_movement_message: Cannot move robot due to unvalidated checksum. Only the Superadmin and other dedicated users can validate the checksum.

jogging_blocked.title: Jogging Not Allowed
jogging_blocked.message: Basic users cannot jog when safety settings are unvalidated.
jogging_blocked.solution_text: Ask your administrator to validate the current safety settings.

help.title: Checksum Management Help
help.what_is_description: Checksum management ensures that robot safety settings remain consistent and validated. When safety-critical parameters are modified, the system generates a new checksum that must be validated by an administrator before basic users can operate the robot.
help.green_checksum_description: Settings are validated and safe for operation
help.red_checksum_description: Settings have changed and require validation
help.basic_users_description: Can only operate when checksum is validated
help.admin_users_description: Can always operate and validate checksums
help.program_control_description: When enabled, basic users cannot execute programs unless the current safety settings match the validated checksum. This ensures operational safety and compliance.

labels.description: Configure how the checksum validation affects robot operation and program execution.
labels.page_explanation: The checksum is a unique identifier of the current robot configuration. It allows quick detection of any parameter changes. The settings displayed below are monitored for checksum calculation.
labels.validation_explanation: Click 'Validate Configuration' to confirm current settings are safe and approved for operation.
labels.status_explanation: Current validation status of the robot configuration.
labels.program_control_description: Control whether basic users can execute programs based on checksum validation status.
labels.block_execution_description: When enabled, basic users cannot execute programs unless the current safety settings match the validated checksum.
labels.no_validation_permission: Only the Superadmin and other dedicated users can validate the checksum.
labels.blocking_enabled_info: Program blocking is enabled. Basic users will be prevented from executing programs when safety settings don't match the validated checksum. Admin and superadmin users can still execute programs.
labels.blocking_disabled_info: Program blocking is disabled. All users can execute programs regardless of checksum validation status.
labels.status_description: Current checksum validation status and its effect on program execution.
labels.coverage_description: List of robot settings that are monitored by the checksum validation system.
